s--from the fierce nineteenth-century debates between the French biologists Geoffroy and Cuvier, who fought over questions of form versus function--to modern theories of how genes dictate body formation. The book's wide-ranging topics include expression patterns of genes, developmental bias, the role of developmental genes, and genetic determinism. Drawing from diverse examples, such as the anatomy of butterflies, giraffes, Siamese twins, and corals, Minelli extends and reformulates important concepts from development, evolution, and the interplay between the two. Presenting the accessible and cutting-edge ideas of evolutionary developmental biology, Forms of Becoming is fascinating reading for anyone interested in genetics and the animal form.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Developmental Biology.2bisacsh  aAdult.  aAmoeba.  aAnimal.  aAnnelid.  aAppendage.  aAquatic animal.  aArachnid.  aArthropod.  aAutonomic nervous system.  aBiogeography.  aBiology.  aBlastomere.  aBlastula.  aCaenorhabditis elegans.  aCaterpillar.  aCell division.  aCestoda.  aCilium.  aCockroach.  aCommon descent.  aCommon species.  aComplication (medicine).  aCrayfish.  aCuticle.  aDevelopmental biology.  aDichotomy.  aDictyostelium.  aDrosophila.  aEarthworm.  aEmbryo.  aEvolution.  aEvolutionary biology.  aEvolutionary developmental biology.  aFertilisation.  aForelimb.  aGamete.  aGemmule.  aGene.  aGermline.  aIchthyostega.  aInformation science.  aInsect.  aInstitution.  aLarva.  aLeave No Trace.  aMammal.  aMating.  aMessenger RNA.  aMetabolism.  aMetacarpal bones.  aMicroorganism.  aMillipede.  aModel organism.  aMolecular biology.  aMollusca.  aMoulting.  aMuscle tissue.  aMuscle.  aMyoepithelia